dogecoin.text:
The brilliance of Dogecoin is in its accidental innovation:

While Bitcoin aimed for financial revolution through complexity and scarcity, Dogecoin achieved mass adoption through simplicity and humor.

It made crypto accessible to millions who found traditional cryptocurrencies https://t.co/Nhr7B8xKNR

Dogecoin evolved far beyond its origins:

• Ranks among the top cryptocurrencies
• Secured Ethereum founder Vitalik Buterin as an advisor
• Launched an entire category of "meme coins"

A few hours of playful programming spawned a multi-billion dollar financial phenomenon.

2021: Dogecoin exploded.

Elon Musk's tweets and massive public interest propelled it to become the 4th largest cryptocurrency, reaching an $88 BILLION market cap.

The same project their creators sold for Honda Civic money transformed into a generational wealth opportunity. https://t.co/2YAbKzCZYk

By 2015, both creators walked away from their creation:

• Palmer left, calling crypto culture "toxic"
• Markus sold ALL his Dogecoin

The payout for his share of this future billion-dollar project?

Just enough to buy a used Honda Civic. https://t.co/dIH01dyDdy

The community (calling themselves "Doge army") started using Dogecoin for good:

They raised $25,000 to send Jamaica's bobsled team to the 2014 Olympics.

Then $55,000 to sponsor a NASCAR driver.

This joke coin was literally changing lives. https://t.co/vz5nmKjHct

Markus reached out to Palmer with a bold proposition to make this joke a reality.

In just a few hours, they created Dogecoin - intentionally making it as ridiculous as possible:

• Comic Sans font
• Dog memes everywhere
• "Mining" renamed to "digging" (because dogs dig) https://t.co/JCh6gacjPI

It started with a joke tweet.

In late 2013, Jackson Palmer (an Adobe engineer) made a silly post about investing in "Dogecoin" - combining two trending topics:

• Cryptocurrencies
• The viral "Doge" meme of a Shiba Inu dog

An IBM engineer named Billy Markus saw the tweet. https://t.co/GCq4gKWWrj
